description: Cellulose nanocrystals are composed of linear polysaccharide chains formed by repeating anhydro-D-glucopyranose units. Each monomeric unit features a six-membered pyranose ring containing one ring oxygen and multiple hydroxyl substituents. These rings are linked sequentially via β-(1→4) glycosidic C–O–C bonds, creating an unbranched backbone with primary alcohol groups located at the C6 positions. In nanocrystals derived via sulfuric acid treatment, a fraction of the surface hydroxyl groups are substituted with sulfate ester groups (O–SO3−), while the underlying glycosidic structure remains unchanged. In composite films, these nanocrystals are physically co-dispersed with xylose and ZnO nanoparticles, where the components associate primarily through noncovalent interactions involving their hydroxyl-rich surfaces.

description:
The molecule is a difluoroboron (BF2) chelate derived from a 2-(2-hydroxyphenyl)benzothiazole-type ligand. Its core consists of a benzothiazole heteroaromatic system—comprising a benzene ring fused to a thiazole ring containing one nitrogen and one sulfur atom—linked at the 2-position to a substituted phenyl ring. This phenyl ring features an ortho phenolic oxygen, which acts as a phenoxide donor for chelation, and a para dodecyloxy substituent consisting of a linear O–(CH2)12–CH3 ether chain. The central boron atom is four-coordinate, bonding to the phenoxide oxygen and the benzothiazole nitrogen to create a six-membered O–B–N chelate ring, while also possessing two B–F bonds.

The synthesis begins with the functionalization of a substituted phenol precursor via Williamson ether formation, alkylating the phenolic oxygen with a dodecyl halide to attach the para-dodecyloxy chain. The benzothiazole framework is subsequently constructed by coupling this substituted component with 2-aminothiophenol through imine formation followed by intramolecular cyclization and oxidation. The final difluoroboron complex is generated by reacting the resulting o-hydroxybenzothiazole ligand with a boron trifluoride source, such as BF3·etherate, in the presence of a base to form the O,N-chelated BF2 structure.

description:
Molecular structure: Vectran is an aromatic polyester polymer derived from the polycondensation of 4-hydroxybenzoic acid and 6-hydroxy-2-naphthoic acid. The polymer backbone consists of repeating units of p-phenylene and 2,6-naphthylene rings linked by ester groups (–C(=O)O–). The structure is characterized by rigid aromatic rings connected directly through the ester linkages, forming a linear, wholly aromatic chain without aliphatic spacers.
